06738nam a22007575i 9780773556041DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735560417 a10.1515/97807735560412doi  a(DE-B1597)656539  a(OCoLC)1080210589  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.04/9qOCoLC223/eng/2023112004aThe Quebec Conference of 1864 :bUnderstanding the Emergence of the Canadian Federation /ced. by Alain-G. Gagnon, Eugénie Brouillet, Guy Laforest. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b23 photos, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- t1864, a Pivotal Year in the Advent of the Canadian Confederation -- tPart One -- tThe Fathers of Confederation and the BNA Act: Constitutional Visions and Models -- tThe Making of a Dominion: The Completion of a Conquest -- tCanadian Constitution-Making in the British World -- tPart Two -- tAvoiding the “iniquitous pit of liberty”: The Centralizing Federalism of Joseph-Édouard Cauchon -- tThe Trustee, the Financier, and the Poet: Cartier, Galt, and D’Arcy McGee -- tA Big Group in a Small Room: Parties and Coalitions at the Quebec Conference -- tGeorge Brown and Oliver Mowat on the Quebec Resolutions and Confederation: Reality and Myth -- tPart Three -- tOpponents of the 1864 Confederation Project: Criticism of the Future Regime -- tConfederation and Corruption: The Republican Critique of the Quebec Resolutions -- tThe Economic Arguments of the Quebec Opponents of Confederation -- tPapineau and the Refusal of Arrangements (1854–67) -- tPart Four -- tIs Rejection of the Melting Pot a Rejection of Modernity? -- tThe Quebec Resolutions and the Ideas Left Behind -- tPrinciples of the 1864 Quebec Conference, Imperial Context, and Historians Joseph Royal and Alfred Duclos De Celles -- tRepresentations of Confederation: Research Prospects -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLike all major events in Canadian history, the Quebec Conference of 1864, an important step on Canada's road to Confederation, deserves to be discussed and better understood. Efforts to revitalize historical memory must take a multidisciplinary and multicultural approach. The Quebec Conference of 1864 expresses a renewed historical interest over the last two decades in both the Quebec-Canada constitutional trajectory and the study of federalism. Contributors from a variety of disciplines argue that a more grounded understanding of the 72 Quebec Resolutions of 1864 is key to interpreting the internal architecture of the contemporary constitutional apparatus in Canada, and a new interpretation is crucial to appraise the progress made over the 150 years since the institution of federalism. The second volume in a series that began with The Constitutions That Shaped Us: A Historical Anthology of Pre-1867 Canadian Constitutions, this book reveals a society in constant transition, as well as the presence of national projects that live in tension with the Canadian federation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBrouillet, Eugénie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrouillet, Eugénie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuckner, Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurelle, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBédard, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator